During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Empress Saimei|ja|斉明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, a devotee of {{ill|Taoism|ja|道教|12=draft|12=draft}}, is said to have built stone fortifications and a grand hall near the summit of Tōnomine, naming it the "Palace of Futatsuki" (両槻宮), according to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>In the Nihon Shoki, the term "観" (kan) is used to describe the Palace of Futatsuki. While it may suggest a Taoist temple ("道観"), it can also mean a "grand hall." Historian Mitsuo Tōyama argues that this ambiguity leaves room for debate. Additionally, the alternative name "Heavenly Palace" (天宮) might refer to the Taoist immortal’s celestial abode or could be a reference to the Buddhist Trayastrimsa Heaven (忉利天宮). Mitsuo Tōyama, *The Origins of the Japanese Emperor: Solving the Mysteries of the Great Kings of Asuka*, Kodansha Gendai Shinsho, 2003, p. 186.</ref> Furthermore, the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft|12=draft}} records in {{ill|858|ja|858th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ten'an 2) that "Tōnomine was identified as the tomb of Fujiwara no Kamatari and included among the 'Ten Imperial Tombs and Four Graves.'" A mid-Heian-period document, *Tōnomine Ryakki* (多武峯略記), states that Kamatari was originally buried in {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|12=draft|12=draft}}, at the current site of {{ill|Ōtorikabuto Shrine|ja|大織冠神社|12=draft|12=draft}} or possibly {{ill|Abo-yama Kofun|ja|阿武山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, but was later reinterred at Tōnomine in Yamato Province.
In the early Meiji period, the temple complex was transformed into {{ill|Tanzan Shrine|ja|談山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} as part of the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft|12=draft}} policies. For more details, see the article on Tanzan Shrine. The "Tōnomine Highway" connects Tanzan Shrine to {{ill|Tomimiyashiro Shrine|ja|等弥神社|12=draft|12=draft}} and intersects with the {{ill|Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山の辺の道|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Shrines and Temples == * {{ill|Tanzan Shrine|ja|談山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Tomimiyashiro Shrine|ja|等弥神社|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Shōrin-ji (Nara)|ja|聖林寺|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Access == [[File:NaraPrefRoad155.JPG|thumb|Prefectural Route 155, with a sign urging caution for pedestrians.]] For those traveling by car, access was previously limited to ascending from the Sakurai side via {{ill|Nara Prefectural Route 37|ja|奈良県道37号桜井吉野線|12=draft|12=draft}}. This route included many narrow, single-lane sections, causing severe congestion during the autumn foliage season. However, the completion tier 6]]
{{draft categories|
}}
{{draft categories| [[Category: of the fully two-lane {{ill|Nara Prefectural Route 155|ja|奈良県道155号多武峯見瀬線|12=draft|12=draft}} in 2009 significantly improved access from the Asuka area. Nonetheless, this road intersects several hiking trails, including one leading from the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, necessitating careful driving. Parking at Tōnomine remains limited, so visitors are advised to use public transportation (buses from {{ill|Sakurai Station (Nara)|ja|桜井駅|12=draft|12=draft}}) or hike (approximately 1.5–2 hours from Ishibutai Kofun).
== Gallery == Tōnomine Highway <gallery> File:Manirijnto01s3200.jpg|Manirin-tō Pagoda File:Tounomine01s3200.jpg|Sansha Shrine File:Tounomine02s3200.jpg|Magaibutsu Buddhist Carvings File:Tounomine03s3200.jpg|Bamboo Forest File:Fudounotaki_tonomine.JPG|Fudō Waterfall File:Yakatabashi tonomine.JPG|Yakata Bridge </gallery>
== Naming == The nearby bus stop uses the variant character 峯 ("Mine") in its name, rendering it as "Tōnomine" (多武峯).
