During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka period|qq=}}, {{ill|Empress Saimei|ja|斉明天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Saimei|qq=}}, a devotee of {{ill|Taoism|ja|道教|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taoism|qq=}}, is said to have built stone fortifications and a grand hall near the summit of Tōnomine, naming it the "Palace of Futatsuki" (両槻宮), according to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}.<ref>In the Nihon Shoki, the term "観" (kan) is used to describe the Palace of Futatsuki. While it may suggest a Taoist temple ("道観"), it can also mean a "grand hall." Historian Mitsuo Tōyama argues that this ambiguity leaves room for debate. Additionally, the alternative name "Heavenly Palace" (天宮) might refer to the Taoist immortal’s celestial abode or could be a reference to the Buddhist Trayastrimsa Heaven (忉利天宮). Mitsuo Tōyama, *The Origins of the Japanese Emperor: Solving the Mysteries of the Great Kings of Asuka*, Kodansha Gendai Shinsho, 2003, p. 186.</ref> Furthermore, the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}} records in {{ill|858|ja|858th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/858|qq=}} (Ten'an 2) that "Tōnomine was identified as the tomb of Fujiwara no Kamatari and included among the 'Ten Imperial Tombs and Four Graves.'" A mid-Heian-period document, *Tōnomine Ryakki* (多武峯略記), states that Kamatari was originally buried in {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Settsu Province|qq=}}, at the current site of {{ill|Ōtorikabuto Shrine|ja|大織冠神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtorikabuto Shrine|qq=}} or possibly {{ill|Abo-yama Kofun|ja|阿武山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abo-yama Kofun|qq=}}, but was later reinterred at Tōnomine in Yamato Province.

In the early Meiji period, the temple complex was transformed into {{ill|Tanzan Shrine|ja|談山神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanzan Shrine|qq=}} as part of the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}} policies. For more details, see the article on Tanzan Shrine. The "Tōnomine Highway" connects Tanzan Shrine to {{ill|Tomimiyashiro Shrine|ja|等弥神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomimiyashiro Shrine|qq=}} and intersects with the {{ill|Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山の辺の道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanobe no Michi|qq=}}.

== Shrines and Temples ==
* {{ill|Tanzan Shrine|ja|談山神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanzan Shrine|qq=}}
* {{ill|Tomimiyashiro Shrine|ja|等弥神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomimiyashiro Shrine|qq=}}
* {{ill|Shōrin-ji (Nara)|ja|聖林寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōrin-ji (Nara)|qq=}}

== Access ==
[[File:NaraPrefRoad155.JPG|thumb|Prefectural Route 155, with a sign urging caution for pedestrians.]]
For those traveling by car, access was previously limited to ascending from the Sakurai side via {{ill|Nara Prefectural Route 37|ja|奈良県道37号桜井吉野線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefectural Route 37|qq=}}. This route included many narrow, single-lane sections, causing severe congestion during the autumn foliage season. However, the Completion tier 6]]

{{translated page|ja|多武峰|version=100113511|comment=Imported full ja history}}

 in 2009 significantly improved access from the Asuka area. Nonetheless, this road intersects several hiking trails, including one leading from the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishibutai Kofun|qq=}}, necessitating careful driving. Parking at Tōnomine remains limited, so visitors are advised to use public transportation (buses from {{ill|Sakurai Station (Nara)|ja|桜井駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakurai Station (Nara)|qq=}}) or hike (approximately 1.5–2 hours from Ishibutai Kofun).

